post_text:
Today - on the 19th anniversary of the September 11 tragedy - we invite our community to join us in remembering and honoring the victims, survivors, recovery workers and responders.

Annually since 2002, the Wissahickon Camerata has hosted a memorial concert and vigil to create a welcoming space of community, reflection, and meditation to consider the events of September 11th, 2001. The program includes passages from literature and patriotic music, as well as some information regarding the events of that day. This video is an abbreviated virtual version of our annual memorial concert, featuring members of the Wissahickon Camerata: https://youtu.be/2Mr38zn-sps

Thank you to WHS Choral Director, John Conahan, and our WHS Camerata students for creating this moving tribute. Wissahickon will Never Forget.

post_text:
Throwback Thursday, Week 10, features Carl Buchholz, Class of 1983: Lawyer, Civic Leader, Volunteer.
Mr. Buchholz was a Philadelphia lawyer who died of cancer on May 23, 2016. At the time of his death, he was a managing partner of the Philadelphia office of DLA Piper International and was previously partner at Blank Rome. He helped George W. Bush created the White House Office of Homeland Security after 9/11 and served as Special Assistant to the President for Homeland Security. In 2000, Mr. Buchholz served as a key member of the Bush-Cheney presidential team that litigated the historic Florida recount. He also served in many charitable positions and was named United Way's volunteer of the year for 2011. For more information:

post_text: Throwback Thursday, Week 9, features Dominique Earland, Class of 2013: MD and PhD graduate student, maternal-child health advocate, STEM supporter. After graduating from WHS, Ms. Earland attended Southern Methodist University as a dual major in Human Rights and Biological Sciences. During her college years she had an interest in pursuing medicine, in particular public health research. After college Ms. Earland attended a 2-year program at University of Maryland where she conducted research on malaria and mentored middle school students to encourage their interest in STEM. She is currently at the University of Minnesota pursuing an MD and PhD and is interested in epidemiology. Learn more:

August 28 at 8:56 AM ·

#WissNation teachers wrapped up 4 days of professional development to prepare for the new school year. Many sessions were held virtually to allow teachers to practice using the digital tools for synchronous instruction along with in-person, school-based training to learn about new safety protocols. Topics of sessions included differentiated instruction, social emotional learning, assessing student learning and much more. We're looking forward to seeing our students on Monday and the start of a great school year!

post_text: Throwback Thursday, Week 8, features Carolyn Stowe Shaner, Class of 1972: Music Teacher, Tennis Coach and Leader. After attending West Chester University, Shaner returned to Wissahickon in 1977, teaching music at Spring House, Shady Grove, Mattison and Blue Bell Elementary Schools. During her 30 years of teaching she coached the girls' high school tennis team and the boys' and girls' tennis teams at the middle school, leading these teams to many league and state championships and undefeated seasons. Learn more:

Throwback Thursday, Week 7, features Donald Hooton, Jr., Class of 1999: Founder and President of the Taylor Hooton Foundation.
The Taylor Hooton Foundation is the national leader in the fight against the use of anabolic steroids and other appearance and performance enhancing substances. He and his father founded the charity in 2004, just one year after the loss of his brother to anabolic steroid use. Mr. Hooton is a highly sought after speaker on this topic and he has appeared on CBS 60 minutes, ESPN and Sports Illustrated. The Hooton Foundation's All Me Assembly program has been presented to almost a million young people, coaches, parents and other adult influencers in middle and high schools and universities across the U.S., Canada and Latin America, as well as U.S. Olympic Committee athletes. Learn more:

post_text: Congratulations to Lindsey Schmidt, Class of 2021, recipient of the 2020 Mini-THON® Rising Diamond Award, which acknowledges an outstanding student volunteer from one of the 280 Mini-THON schools. Over the past year, Lindsey has emerged and developed as a leader, energized and inspired others, brought innovative ideas to Mini-THON and raised awareness and funds for our Mini-THON event, as well as Four Diamonds. Lindsey exemplifies the leadership and character of the Mini-THON program and has proven to be a role model for her peers. Way to go, Lindsey! #WissPride

post_text: Throwback Thursday, Week 4 features Kevin Witchey, Class of 1981: Scholar Athlete, Mentor and Counselor. Mr. Witchey attended Temple University on a full athletic scholarship for football and became involved in several community service organizations, including The Fifth Quarter Club where student-athletes mentored students at local Philadelphia schools. After graduating, Mr. Witchey worked for the Montgomery County Youth Center counseling adjudicated students and writing recommendations to the juvenile court. In 1995, he returned to Wissahickon School District in the role of Home and School Visitor to work with at-risk students in not only the school district but in various community groups. Learn more about Mr. Witchey:

post_text: Throwback Thursday, Week 3 features Kara Aiello, Class of 1990: Writer, Dancer, and Recreational Activities Therapist. Ms. Aiello has Osteogenesis Imperfecta (brittle bone disease) and has been in a wheelchair for her entire life, but that hasn't stopped her from accomplishing her goals. For the majority of her dance career, she danced with Kardon Institute of Performing Arts, and also at The Kennedy Center in 1994, The Clef Club in Philadelphia and New Orleans, and talent shows on two Carnival Cruises. Ms. Aiello went on to get her master’s degree in social work and a certification in therapeutic recreation. She has worked with the geriatric population and she founded American Dance Wheels which encourages mobility for those with disabilities. Learn more about Ms. Aiello:

post_text: Congratulations to Anna Alberti ’20, one of only 17 seniors in Montgomery County selected as a 2020 Dannehower Award winner by the Triangle Club of Montgomery County. The award recognizes students who “embody the very best and brightest that Montgomery County has to offer in the field of sports, scholarship, and service.” Throughout high school, Anna participated in Girls' Varsity Swimming and Water Polo, serving as varsity captain in 10th and 11th grades and winning a number of athletic honors/awards. An exemplary student and member of the National Honor Society, she was also actively involved in extra-curricular academic and service activities, including serving as headchairman of Mini-THON, WEOF student representative, Wiss Link and Wiss Pals. Way to go, Anna! #WissPride

post_text: LGE 3rd grader, Troy Smith, decided to use a STEM/Memorial Day themed assignment to help others. Third graders were asked to use items from around their house to create an American flag. Troy handily completed the project, making a flag out of wood. Then, he decided that with the help of his brother - 1st grader, Elliott – to turn the assignment into a community service project to raise money for the Veterans In Need Foundation. The brothers continued to make flags that they sold on Memorial Day with the goal of raising $100. Everything was sold in less than an hour, raising $450. The boys also received requests for more and have continued making them. #WissCares #WissPride

To remember and honor those who died in service to our country, those who have died of COVID-19 and those who are on the front lines battling the disease, #WissNation is invited to participate in the National Moment of Remembrance on Memorial Day, May 25th. The annual event encourages Americans, wherever they are at 3 pm on Memorial Day to sound Taps (if able) or pause for one minute to remember those who have died in military service to the United States. Our very own WHS Band Teacher and Army Veteran Mike Hood will be joining hundreds of people across America who have signed up to sound Taps for "Taps Across America".
http://ow.ly/8eug50zNLjL

TAPSFORVETERANS.ORG

April 20 at 2:50 PM ·

Each week, we will spotlight some of the creative ways we are doing virtual teaching and learning! This week, our focus is on Ms. Cantwell’s Class at Lower Gwynedd. Ms. Cantwell uses her computer as a Smart Board where she can simulate exactly what students would see on the Smart Board in the regular classroom. She shares math journal pages, highlights important information, and solves problems! She has also been rolling out self-directed lessons where students follow along virtually. Since students are currently studying the American Revolution, they are taking a virtual field trip next week to the Museum of the American Revolution to explore the different exhibits and artifacts AND a virtual walking tour of Philadelphia to visit historic sites such as Independence Hall and the Liberty Bell. #WissLearns

post_text:
Dear WSD Community: Important supplemental update, hot off the press: We just received word that all schools across the state of Pennsylvania have been ordered closed by Governor Wolf for the balance of the academic school year. We had been anticipating such an announcement, and I’m frankly thankful it came sooner rather than later.

This of course generates a whirlwind of questions. What’s the status of annual, year-end activities? How will scheduling for next year be finalized? What about summer programs? And many, many more. We will endeavor to answer all these important questions as soon as we can, with as much detail as possible. Going to take some time to get to everything, but we’re on it.

Meanwhile, hang in there. We got this.

Dr. James Crisfield, Superintendent

post_text: #WissNation: We have had a great response to our 2020 Census Competition between Ambler, Lower Gwynedd and Blue Bell. Thanks so much to those who completed the census and contributed to the growth! Ambler and Whitpain went up 10% percent since April 1st and Lower Gwynedd follows closely behind with an 8% percent increase. We’re one more step closer to our goal! Here’s a tip: to those who live or know someone who lives in an apartment, please ask them to participate in the census because census workers are not permitted to enter apartment complexes. This will make the biggest difference in the Census Count. Keep up the great effort, stay safe and spread the word! Allison Meng and Anika Rastogi, WMS

post_text:
WSD families! Two WMS students, Allison Meng and Anika Rastogi have an IMPORTANT PSA:
Many aspects of our community depend and benefit from the 2020 Census, including our school, hospitals, and roads, among others. Therefore, your family's participation is very important. However, ongoing statistics show that only 39% of Ambler, 50% of Whitpain, and 49% of Lower Gwynedd have responded to the Census. You can help increase these numbers! Let's see which township will be the first to reach the healthy zone of 86-100%! The competition is on now! Help be the difference by reminding your family, friends, relatives, and others to complete the census. Your support is much needed and appreciated. Spread the word!

post_text:
In the midst of the incredible upheaval created by COVID, there continues to be some truly WONDERFUL things happening in #WissNation that demonstrate our community’s kindness, creativity and resilience – a reminder that ‘every cloud has a silver lining’. With that in mind, as best we can, we hope to lift spirits with a focus on all things uplifting and upworthy in a weekly roundup called Wissahickon Silver Linings. We invite you to view our first edition, which includes photos of our families, friends and staff along with words of encouragement, family fun activity ideas, shout outs to our many #WissNation helpers and spotlights on the creative ways our community is staying connected.
http://ow.ly/5PIn50z1fXi

ACTIVITY: Who loves LEGOS? We'd love to see your LEGO creations! Leave a comment with your photos or videos. We'll post some of your creations later this week! #WissAtHome

_________________________________________________________________
Please use these activities to share the positive moments in your homes during our school closure.

You may leave a comment with photos and videos for each activity. All videos should be NO MORE THAN 60 SECONDS.

During the week, we will publish a collection of the photos and videos submitted into an album on Facebook and share them on Twitter and Instagram.

The district communications department reviews all comments, photos, and videos posted on its social media channels. We reserve the opportunity to remove comments that are negative and/or inappropriate.

Please DO NOT share your photos and videos through direct message (i.e. Facebook Messenger, Twitter, DM, or Instagram DM). We do not respond to messages received through these messengers.

If you have children between the ages of zero to five, sign up for the Wissahickon Tips4Kids program. Tips are tailored to specific age groups - babies (0-1), toddlers (2-3), and preschoolers (4-5). Each week during the school year, you receive a literacy tip to help your child(ren) learn to love reading. You do not need to be a resident of the Wissahickon School District to enroll in this program - it is open to everyone! #WissReads

Sign Up: https://www.wsdweb.org/our-community/tips4kids

post_text:
UPDATE: All kindergarten registration appointments are CANCELLED. All Wissahickon schools and buildings are closed through March 27:

As a precautionary measure, WSD is limiting the exposure between our staff and community. Previously scheduled registration appointments with parents/guardians for enrollment in the District will continue, but if you or any family member is experiencing cold or flu-like symptoms or you have traveled outside of the U.S. within the last 30 days, please contact the District Registrar at registrar@wsdweb.org to reschedule your appointment for a future date. As a reminder, children are not needed at the registration appointment and only one parent/guardian is required for the meeting. This district is NOT accepting walk-in registration inquiries or appointments.
To complete the registration process for your student(s), please visit the WSD website for detailed instructions: https://www.wsdweb.org/departments/registration

As a reminder, children are not needed at the registration appointment and only one parent/guardian is required for the meeting. This district is NOT accepting walk-in registration inquiries or appointments.
To complete the registration process for your student(s), please visit the WSD website for detailed instructions: https://www.wsdweb.org/departments/registration

• 11:00 AM – WMS
• 11:05 AM – WHS
• 11:50 AM – Elementary Schools

REMINDER: When you fill out the 2020 Census you help to determine how many seats your state gets in congress and also help to ensure that Montgomery County receives its fair share of the billions of dollars of federal funding to support things like:
• Child Care
• Nutrition, School Lunch and Breakfast Programs
• Career, Technical and Workforce Training
• Title I, Special Education and Federal PELL Grants
• Medicaid and Children’s Health Insurance
• Head Start, and many other programs
With just a 5% undercount in the 2020 Census, Montgomery County would stand to lose 73 million dollars of these funds each year for the next 10 years. It is critical that everyone is counted!
By April 1, 2020, every home will receive an invitation to participate in the 2020 Census. You may complete the Census online, by phone, or by mail. Please complete the census for your family and encourage your friends, relatives and neighbors to do the same.

On February 29, 2020, WMS sent the following team of students to compete in the You Be the Chemist Challenge at Dow Chemical in Collegeville: Parth Patel, Connor Ginnane, Allison Meng and Kenneth Cobbs

The You Be The Chemist Challenge® is an interactive academic contest that encourages students in grades 5-8 to explore chemistry concepts and their real-world applications. The Challenge provides a unique opportunity for a variety of individuals and organizations—including schools, members of the chemical industry, educators, and other community partners—to come together and show their support for STEM education.

These students worked together as a team during the competition and finished in second place! #WissPride

post_text:
The Wissahickon School District (WSD) is embarking on a months-long study of how students who receive special education are served in its schools. The study is being conducted by WestEd, in partnership with The Improve Group, and will include: A comprehensive review of data and documents; Individual and group interviews with staff; Family input and School visits.

Beginning in late March 2020, evaluators from WestEd, who are former school and district administrators, will be surveying families, visiting WSD schools, and meeting with staff. More information will be shared prior to each visit/event. The primary purpose of the study is to examine ways WSD might be able to capture efficiencies in its special education model and program without compromising the quality of the services provided to students. Results will be shared publicly at the study’s conclusion (late summer or early fall 2020).

Any questions can be directed to Dr. Gary Abbamont, Assistant Superintendent of Schools via email (gabbamont@wsdweb.org) or phone (215/619-8000, x1125).

post_text: WHS Band Teacher, Mr. Hood, and his NOLA Brass Band – The Hoppin’ John Orchestra -played on Fox 29 for Mardi Gras this Tuesday. The band has been performing since 1996 and has two records out with a 3rd scheduled for release this fall. Enjoy the shots from Tuesday’s celebration. #WissPride
shared_text:
The Hoppin' John Orchestra
February 26 at 5:45 PM ·

The shiniest.
Mardi Gras 2020 with the HJO.
Starting with a TV appearance....moving onto to two Mardi Gras parties for my students at school with 2 King Cakes and mocktails and then.... the apex of a BIG house for both seatings at Chris's Jazz Cafe where we played our purple, green and gold hearts out for three sets.
Dang y'all....
That was the best Tuesday I remember ever having!
A HUGE thank you to everyone who came out to see us and especially to my long-serving band mates who quite literally make it all possible. And Chef Mark!!!
The cherry on top?
An actual New Orleanian who was stranded in Philly on Mardi Gras day was amazed at the authenticity of the music and food and general level of revelry and let me know very enthusiastically!
#NOLABrassBandPhiladelphia
A few shots from the set at the FOX 29 morning show and then Chris's Jazz Cafe.

post_text:
WMS Interact and the Blue Bell Rotary were honored to present Grayson Ruffner with the first “Rising Star Award” for his participation in Wissahickon Middle School Interact program.

He was selected by Ms. Duke, the Faculty advisor, because of his commitment to Interact and the community. He attends every meeting with a positive attitude and a willingness to help everyone. He will even tell coaches that he will miss practice to attend meeting. Not many 7th and 8th graders are willing to skip sports to help others. Grayson does it with a smile on his face.

Over the past three years, Grayson has helped with every project from making gift tags for holiday gifts for patients who have not had visitors in over a year to making inspirational posters and cards for a parent of a middle school student who is awaiting a heart transplant. He has helped in our fundraising activities that help to support the Veteran’s Memorial and the Rotary’s school in Africa. He does everything with great gusto and enthusiasm!

So much Wissahickon pride for Grayson!

post_text: LGE 5th Graders provided a lesson to the School Board about the Sixth Amendment via song and dance. The six students created an essay, Power Point and skit as part of a Citizenship Challenge run by The Rendell Center for Civics and Civic Engagement. LGE placed as a top 10 finalist out of 200 schools that entered the contest, winning a trip to the National Constitution Center, a $250 citizenship award and a mock trial curriculum package. The students’ presentation addressed the following: Which part of the Bill of Rights do you think is the most important and continues to exert the greatest impact on Americans today? #WissLearns
